title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: scMultiSim simulation tool single-cell multi-omics data. can simulate RNA counts, ATAC-seq data, RNA velocity, spatial locations continuous discrete cell populations. can model effects gene regulatory networks (GRN), chromatin accessibility, cell-cell interactions simulated data. tutorial, demonstrate use scMultiSim simulate multi-omics data different biological effects, including: Simulating true RNA counts ATAC-seq data Controlling cell population GRN effects Adding technical variation batch effect true counts Adjusting parameters control different biological effects first load package: scMultiSim first generates true RNA counts, add technical variation batch effect true counts. simulate true counts, call sim_true_counts(options) options list. can use scmultisim_help() get help options, like scmulti_help("num.cells") get help options specific function.
code: library("scMultiSim") scmultisim_help("options")

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: start, define utility function modify list. minimal input scMultiSim differentiation tree, can optionally provide ground truth GRN cell-cell interactions. differentiation tree R phylo object, can created using e.g. ape::read.tree() ape::rtree(). controls cell population structure: node tree represent cell type, connected nodes indicate differentiation relationship cell types. scMultiSim provides explicit control cell population structure preserving effects (GRN Cell-Cell Interactions), can generate cell trajectory clustering structure want, especially useful benchmarking trajectory inference clustering methods. generating continuous population, tree specifies cell differentiation trajectory; generating discrete population, tips tree clusters (cell types terminal cell states). scMultiSim also provides three differentiation trees. Phyla5() Phyla3() return bifurcating trees 5 3 leaves respectively. Phyla1() returns single branch, can useful don’t want specific trajectory.  need n cell clusters without specific trajectory, can use code like generate simple tree n leaves. GRN data frame 3 columns, representing target, regulator, effect. target regulator gene names, can integers strings. effect numeric value, indicating effect regulator target. scMultiSim provides two sample GRNs, GRN_params_100 GRN_params_1139, contain 100 1139 genes respectively. Let’s load first.
code: library(dplyr) list_modify <- function (curr_list, ...) {   args <- list(...)   for (i in names(args)) {     curr_list[[i]] <- args[[i]]   }   curr_list } par(mfrow=c(1,2)) Phyla5(plotting = TRUE) ##  ## Phylogenetic tree with 5 tips and 4 internal nodes. ##  ## Tip labels: ##   1, 2, 3, 4, 5 ##  ## Rooted; includes branch lengths. Phyla3(plotting = TRUE) ##  ## Phylogenetic tree with 3 tips and 2 internal nodes. ##  ## Tip labels: ##   1, 2, 3 ##  ## Rooted; includes branch lengths. # It's not possible to plot Phyla1() because it only contains 1 branch connecting two nodes. Phyla1() ##  ## Phylogenetic tree with 1 tips and 1 internal nodes. ##  ## Tip labels: ##   A ##  ## Rooted; includes branch lengths. # tree with four leaves ape::read.tree(text = "(A:1,B:1,C:1,D:1);") ##  ## Phylogenetic tree with 4 tips and 1 internal nodes. ##  ## Tip labels: ##   A, B, C, D ##  ## Unrooted; includes branch lengths. data(GRN_params_100) GRN_params <- GRN_params_100 head(GRN_params) ##   regulated.gene regulator.gene regulator.effect ## 1             16             10         1.768699 ## 2             29             10         1.675360 ## 3             62             10         3.723509 ## 4             55             10         2.866182 ## 5             81             80         4.020744 ## 6             73             80         2.353371

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: Now, create options list simulation session. following example, simulate 500 cells 50 CIFs. number genes determined option num.genes number genes GRN. num.genes specified, number genes number unique genes GRN, plus fraction genes regulated genes. controlled option unregulated.gene.ratio (default 0.1). Since GRN_params contains 100 gene names, 10% genes added simulation, number genes simulated data 110. don’t need simulate GRN effects, simply set GRN = NA. cif.sigma controls variance CIFs. Usually, cif.sigma = 0.1, trajectory clear, cif.sigma = 1, trajectory noisy. use cif.sigma = 0.5 example. also .velocity option use Kinetic model simulate RNA velocity data.
code: options <- list(   rand.seed = 0,   GRN = GRN_params,   num.cells = 1000,   num.cifs = 50,   cif.sigma = 0.5,   tree = Phyla5(),   diff.cif.fraction = 0.8,   do.velocity = TRUE )

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: Note minimal input scMultiSim cell population structure (differentiation tree) number cells. can omit GRN using GRN = NA:
code: options <- list(   GRN = NA   num.cells = 1000,   tree = Phyla5(), )

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: Now run simulation check kind data returned result: results contains following important data: - counts: true RNA counts (genes x cells) - atac_counts: true ATAC-seq data (regions x cells) - cell_meta: cell meta data, including cell population labels
code: results <- sim_true_counts(options) ## Time spent: 0.29 mins names(results) ##  [1] ".grn"             "unspliced_counts" ".options"         ".n"               ##  [5] "region_to_gene"   "atacseq_data"     "giv"              "kinetic_params"   ##  [9] "num_genes"        "velocity"         "cif"              "hge_scale"        ## [13] "counts"           "cell_meta"        "atac_counts"      "region_to_tf"     ## [17] "grn_params"       "cell_time"

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: can visualize true counts ATAC-seq data using plot_tsne(data, labels):   Since also RNA velocity enabled, results also contains following data: - velocity: true RNA velocity (genes x cells) - unspliced_counts: true unspliced RNA counts (genes x cells)    can inspect gene-gene correlation using plot_gene_module_cor_heatmap(results):
code: plot_tsne(log2(results$counts + 1),          results$cell_meta$pop,          legend = 'pop', plot.name = 'True RNA Counts Tsne') plot_tsne(log2(results$atacseq_data + 1),          results$cell_meta$pop,          legend = 'pop', plot.name = 'True ATAC-seq Tsne') plot_rna_velocity(results, arrow.length = 2) ## $raw ##  ## $normalized ##  ## $knn_normalized plot_gene_module_cor_heatmap(results) ## NULL

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: scMultiSim, user use num.cifs control total number diff-CIF non-diff-CIFs. number CIFs large enough represent cell population structure gene information. default, num.cifs set 50, good starting point cases. However, gene’s base expression affected two random diff-CIF entries, therefore large number genes, may similar expression patterns, may ideal. recommended increase num.cifs 50-100 2000 genes. small number genes (less 1000), can also decrease num.cifs 20-40.

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: can also simulate discrete cell population setting discrete.cif = TRUE. case, tip tree one cell type, therefore 5 clusters following result.
code: options <- list(   rand.seed = 0,   GRN = GRN_params,   num.cells = 1000,   num.cifs = 50,   tree = Phyla5(),   diff.cif.fraction = 0.8,   discrete.cif = TRUE )  results <- sim_true_counts(options) ## Time spent: 0.18 mins plot_tsne(log2(results$counts + 1),          results$cell_meta$pop,          legend = 'pop', plot.name = 'True RNA Counts Tsne')

what: Adjusting the Effect of Cell Population
title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: scMultiSim, differentiation tree provides explicit control cell population. effect tree can adjusted option diff.cif.fraction, controls many CIFs affected cell population. larger diff.cif.fraction, effect cell population larger may see clearer trajectory well separated clusters. smaller diff.cif.fraction, resulting RNA counts affected factors, GRN. Now let’s visualize trajectory different diff.cif.fraction values:
code: options <- list(   rand.seed = 0,   GRN = GRN_params,   num.cells = 1000,   num.cifs = 50,   tree = Phyla5(),   diff.cif.fraction = 0.8 )  results <- sim_true_counts(         options %>% list_modify(diff.cif.fraction = 0.2)) ## Time spent: 0.09 mins plot_tsne(log2(results$counts + 1),          results$cell_meta$pop,          legend = 'pop', plot.name = 'RNA Counts (diff.cif.fraction = 0.2)') results <- sim_true_counts(         options %>% list_modify(diff.cif.fraction = 0.8)) ## Time spent: 0.09 mins plot_tsne(log2(results$counts + 1),          results$cell_meta$pop,          legend = 'pop', plot.name = 'RNA Counts (diff.cif.fraction = 0.8)')

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: inherent cell heterogeneity controlled non-diff-CIF, sampled normal distribution mean cif.mean standard deviation cif.sigma. Therefore, larger cif.sigma , larger inherent cell heterogeneity . Now, let’s visualize effect cif.sigma:
code: options <- list(   rand.seed = 0,   GRN = GRN_params,   num.cells = 1000,   num.cifs = 50,   tree = Phyla5(),   diff.cif.fraction = 0.8,   cif.sigma = 0.5 )  results <- sim_true_counts(         options %>% list_modify(cif.sigma = 0.1)) ## Time spent: 0.09 mins plot_tsne(log2(results$counts + 1),          results$cell_meta$pop,          legend = 'pop', plot.name = 'RNA Counts (cif.sigma = 0.1)') results <- sim_true_counts(         options %>% list_modify(cif.sigma = 1.0)) ## Time spent: 0.09 mins plot_tsne(log2(results$counts + 1),          results$cell_meta$pop,          legend = 'pop', plot.name = 'RNA Counts (cif.sigma = 1.0)')

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: set .velocity = FALSE, scMultiSim simulate RNA counts using Beta-Poisson model, faster doesn’t output RNA velocity. using Beta-Possion model, scMultiSim provides intrinsic.noise parameter control intrinsic noise transcription process. default, intrinsic.noise set 1, means true counts sampled Beta-Poisson model. set intrinsic.noise smaller value like 0.5, true counts 0.5 * (theoretical mean) + 0.5 * (sampled Beta-Poisson model). intrinsic noise make encoded effects (e.g. GRN) harder inferred.
code: options <- list(   rand.seed = 0,   GRN = GRN_params,   num.cells = 1000,   num.cifs = 50,   tree = Phyla5(),   diff.cif.fraction = 0.8,   intrinsic.noise = 1 )  results <- sim_true_counts(         options %>% list_modify(intrinsic.noise = 0.5)) ## Time spent: 0.09 mins plot_tsne(log2(results$counts + 1),          results$cell_meta$pop,          legend = 'pop', plot.name = 'RNA Counts (intrinsic.noise = 0.5)') results <- sim_true_counts(         options %>% list_modify(intrinsic.noise = 1)) ## Time spent: 0.09 mins plot_tsne(log2(results$counts + 1),          results$cell_meta$pop,          legend = 'pop', plot.name = 'RNA Counts (intrinsic.noise = 1)')

title: Simulating Multimodal Single-cell Datasets
text: First, call following function check usage dynamic GRN. use Phyla1() differentiation tree remove effect trajectory. Additionally, can use discrete.cif = TRUE simulate discrete cell population. results$cell_specific_grn list containing gene effects matrix cell. row target column regulator. corresponding gene names displayed column row names. Since set cell.per.step = 3, expect adjacent 3 cells share GRN:
code: scmultisim_help("dynamic.GRN") ## Dynamic GRN deletes and creates some edges in the GRN in each epoch. ## One epoch contains multiple steps, and the change is done gradually in steps. ## The specific GRN at each step will be used by one or more cells sequentially. ## When an epoch is done, another epoch will start. ##  ## Available options for dynamic.GRN: ##   - seed: the random seed ##   - num.steps: number of steps in each epoch. ##   - cell.per.step: how many cells share the GRN in the same step. ##   - involved.genes: a new edge will only be created within these specified genes. ##       The default value is NA, which will use all existing genes in the GRN. ##   - num.changing.edges: if < 1, it means the portion of edges added/deleted in each epoch. ##       if >= 1, it means the number of edges added/deleted in each epoch. ##   - create.tf.edges: whether a new edge can connect two TFs in the GRN. ##   - weight.mean: the mean value of the weight for a newly created edge. ##       The default value is NA, meaning that it will use the mean value of the input GRN. ##   - weight.sd: the standard deviation of the weight for a newly created edge. ##  ## See the returned list for the default values. ## NULL options_ <- list(   rand.seed = 0,   GRN = GRN_params,   num.cells = 1000,   num.cifs = 50,   tree = Phyla1(),   diff.cif.fraction = 0.8,   do.velocity = FALSE,   dynamic.GRN = list(     cell.per.step = 3,     num.changing.edges = 5,     weight.mean = 0,     weight.sd = 4   ) )  results <- sim_true_counts(options_) ## Time spent: 0.09 mins # GRN for cell 1 (first 10 rows) results$cell_specific_grn[[1]][1:10,] ##           2        6       10       19 80 91 ## 1  2.250484 1.824607 1.941613 4.268812  0  0 ## 2  0.000000 0.000000 0.000000 0.000000  0  0 ## 3  2.184071 0.000000 0.000000 0.000000  0  0 ## 4  1.634807 0.000000 0.000000 0.000000  0  0 ## 5  4.677883 4.301893 2.090473 4.047174  0  0 ## 6  0.000000 0.000000 0.000000 0.000000  0  0 ## 7  3.306285 2.673968 2.414780 3.548154  0  0 ## 8  2.707510 4.653263 1.357980 1.829304  0  0 ## 9  1.501430 1.970649 4.359262 3.915318  0  0 ## 10 0.000000 0.000000 0.000000 0.000000  0  0 print(all(results$cell_specific_grn[[1]] == results$cell_specific_grn[[2]])) ## [1] TRUE print(all(results$cell_specific_grn[[2]] == results$cell_specific_grn[[3]])) ## [1] TRUE print(all(results$cell_specific_grn[[3]] == results$cell_specific_grn[[4]])) ## [1] FALSE

title: Simulating Spatial Cell-Cell Interactions
text: scMultiSim can simulate spatial cell-cell interactions. , need provide cci option list. following code print instructions use cci option. Now, prepare ligand-receptor interaction database. pretty similar GRN network: data frame three columns, specifying target, regulator, effect, respectively. target regulator columns contain IDs target regulator genes. following example, two ligand-receptor pairs interacting two neighboring cells. can now simulate spatial cell-cell interactions. scMultiSim, CCI network cell-type based, means cell type pair, can different CCI network sampled database defined . , set step.size 0.5, differentiation tree divided segments length 0.5, segment treated cell type CCI. set cell.type.interaction random, CCI network cell type pair randomly sampled database. results$cell_meta contain cell type information used CCI. can plot cell spatial locations using plotCellLoc(). arrows indicate cell-cell interactions two cells (first ligand-receptor pair).  cell locations available results$cci_locs.
code: library(scMultiSim)  scmultisim_help("cci") ##  ## To enable simulating cell-cell interaction, the value should be a list including ## the following names: ##  ## - params: (data.frame) ##     The spatial effect between neighbor cells. ##     It should be a data frame similar to the GRN parameter. ## - step.size: (number, optional) ##     If using continuous population, use this step size to further divide the ##     cell types on the tree. For example, if the tree only has one branch 1 -> 2 ##     and the branch length is 1 while the step size is 0.34, there will be totally ##     three cell types: 1_2_1, 1_2_2, 1_2_3. ## - cell.type.interaction: ("random" or a matrix) ##     The interaction level between different cell types. ##     They act as factors multiplied to the ligand effect. ##     Supply the string "random" to let scMultiSim generate these factors randomly. ##     Otherwise, use cci_cell_type_params() to generate the template data structure. ##     See the help of this method for more info. ## - max.neighbors: (integer from 1 to 4, optional) ##     Constraint the maxinum number of neighbors with CCI for each cell. ##     The neighbors with CCI will be randomly sampled.  ## ## NULL lig_params <- data.frame(   target    = c(101, 102),   regulator = c(103, 104),   effect    = c(5.2, 5.9) ) data(GRN_params_100)  options_ <- list(   rand.seed = 0,   GRN = GRN_params_100,   num.genes = 200,   num.cells = 300,   num.cifs = 50,   tree = Phyla3(),   intrinsic.noise = 0.5,   cci = list(     params = lig_params,     max.neighbors = 4,     cell.type.interaction = "random",     step.size = 0.5   ) )  results <- sim_true_counts(options_) ## CCI simulation is enabled. ## Get CIF...100..200..300..Done ## Get params...Done ## Simulating...50..100..150..200..250..300.. ## Time spent: 5.35 mins plot_cell_loc(results) head(results$cci_locs) ##        x  y ## cell1 26 26 ## cell2 24 33 ## cell3 30 22 ## cell4 20 16 ## cell5 24 27 ## cell6 27 26

title: Simulating Spatial Cell-Cell Interactions
text: Simulating spatial cell-cell interactions can computationally expensive. Setting two options can speed simulation: First , recommended set experimental speed.= T option. option become default later versions scMultiSim. Next, possible set CCI option start.layer = n_cells, n_cells number cells. scMultiSim simulates spatial dataset following n_cells steps, adding one cell spatial grid step. final step outputted result. CCI option start.layer can used start simulation specific time step. set n_cells, simulation skip previous steps adding cells . default, start.layer set n_cells number cells greater 800.

title: Simulating Spatial Cell-Cell Interactions

title: Simulating Spatial Cell-Cell Interactions
text: scMultiSim ships several built-spatial layouts. enhanced layout default layout, cells added grid one one. adding new cell, higher probability placed near existing cells cell type.  option .type.prob decides probability new cell placed near existing cells cell type. default, 0.8; use lower value, new cell placed randomly.  layers layout arranges cells layers.  islands layout put cell types center like islands, others around . may specify cell type islands format islands:1,2,3. number can looked results$cci_cell_types.
code: # helper function to add `layout` to options, to make the code more readable spatial_options <- function (...) {   cci_opt <- list(     params = lig_params,     max.neighbors = 4,     start.layer = 300,     grid.size = 28,     cell.type.interaction = "random"   )   list(     rand.seed = 0,     GRN = GRN_params_100,     num.genes = 200,     num.cells = 300,     num.cifs = 50,     tree = Phyla3(),     cci = c(cci_opt, list(...))   ) }   results <- sim_true_counts(spatial_options(   layout = "enhanced" )) ## CCI simulation is enabled. ## Spatial: only the last layer will be simulated. ## Get CIF...100..200..300..Done ## Get params...Done ## Simulating...300.. ## Time spent: 0.42 mins plot_cell_loc(results, show.arrows = FALSE) results <- sim_true_counts(spatial_options(   layout = "enhanced",   same.type.prob = 0.1 )) ## CCI simulation is enabled. ## Spatial: only the last layer will be simulated. ## Get CIF...100..200..300..Done ## Get params...Done ## Simulating...300.. ## Time spent: 0.43 mins plot_cell_loc(results, show.arrows = FALSE) results <- sim_true_counts(spatial_options(   layout = "layers" )) ## CCI simulation is enabled. ## Spatial: only the last layer will be simulated. ## Get CIF...100..200..300..Done ## Get params...Done ## Simulating...300.. ## Time spent: 0.42 mins plot_cell_loc(results, show.arrows = FALSE) results$cci_cell_types ##   4_5   5_2   5_3 4_1_1 4_1_2  ##     1     2     3     4     5 results <- sim_true_counts(spatial_options(   # cell type 4_1_2 should be the island   layout = "islands:5" )) ## CCI simulation is enabled. ## Spatial: only the last layer will be simulated. ## Get CIF...100..200..300..Done ## Get params...Done ## Simulating...300.. ## Time spent: 0.42 mins plot_cell_loc(results, show.arrows = FALSE)

title: Simulating Spatial Cell-Cell Interactions
text: also possible layout cells programmatically. layout option can function takes cell type information returns spatial locations cells: example, following layout function place cells sequentially grid, starting bottom-left corner.
code: # grid_size is a number # cell_types is an integer vector, representing the cell types function(grids_size, cell_types) {   # return a matrix with two columns, representing the x and y coordinates of the cells   return matrix(nrow = 2, ncol = ncells) } results <- sim_true_counts(spatial_options(   layout = function (grid_size, cell_types) {     ncells <- length(cell_types)     new_locs <- matrix(nrow = ncells, ncol = 2)     # for each cell...     for (i in 1:ncells) {       # ...place it in the grid       new_locs[i,] <- c(i %% grid_size, i %/% grid_size)     }     return(new_locs)   } )) ## CCI simulation is enabled. ## Spatial: only the last layer will be simulated. ## Get CIF...100..200..300..Done ## Get params...Done ## Simulating...300.. ## Time spent: 0.42 mins plot_cell_loc(results, show.arrows = FALSE)

title: Simulating Spatial Cell-Cell Interactions
text: Next, demonstrate use custom layout function create spatial domains. want three spatial domains layered layout, four cell types. cell type different probability domain. following layout function job: First , generates set locations form circular shape. Next, assigns cells locations; leftmost cell selected origin. , can create layered layout sorting locations based euclidian distance origin. three domains determined distance origin. matrix ct_matrix specifies probability cell type domain. Finally, sample cells based probabilities assign domains. Inspecting result, can see three spatial domains, middle one contains mix two cell types.
code: layout_fn <- function(grid_size, final_types) {   ncells <- length(final_types)   grid_center <- c(round(grid_size / 2), round(grid_size / 2))   all_locs <- gen_clutter(ncells, grid_size, grid_center)   # center is bottom-left   left_ones <- which(all_locs[,1] == min(all_locs[,1]))   new_center <<- all_locs[left_ones[which.min(all_locs[left_ones, 2])],]   dist_to_center <- sqrt(colSums((t(all_locs) - new_center)^2))   new_locs <- all_locs[order(dist_to_center),]   # prob of a cell type being in a zone (cell_type x zone)   ct_matrix <- matrix(c(     0.9, 0.1, 0.0,     0.1, 0.8, 0.1,     0.1, 0.7, 0.2,     0.0, 0.1, 0.9   ), nrow = 4, byrow = TRUE)   # number of cells per type   ct_pop <- c(160, 80, 100, 140)   pop_mtx <- round(ct_matrix * ct_pop)   if (sum(pop_mtx) != ncells) {     diffrence <- ncells - sum(pop_mtx)     pop_mtx[1, 1] <- pop_mtx[1, 1] + diffrence   }   # number of cells per zone   zone_pop <- colSums(pop_mtx)   # assign cells to zones   cs <- cumsum(zone_pop)   # sample cells   cell_idx <- lapply(1:3, function(izone) {     sample(rep(1:4, pop_mtx[,izone]), zone_pop[izone])   }) %>% unlist()   locs <<- new_locs[order(cell_idx),]   zone_gt <<- rep(1:3, zone_pop)[order(cell_idx)]   return(locs) } results <- sim_true_counts(list(   num.cells = 500,   num.genes = 300,   num.cifs = 40,   GRN = NA,   speed.up = T,   cif.sigma = 0.8,   tree = ape::read.tree(text = "(A:1,B:1,C:1,D:1);"),   diff.cif.fraction = 0.8,   discrete.cif = T,   discrete.pop.size = as.integer(c(120,150,100,130)),   cci = list(     params = lig_params,     max.neighbors = 4,     start.layer = 500,     cell.type.interaction = "random",     layout = layout_fn,     step.size = 1   ) )) ## Experimental speed optimization enabled. ## CCI simulation is enabled. ## Spatial: only the last layer will be simulated. ## Get CIF...Get params...Done ## Simulating...500.. ## Time spent: 0.26 mins plot_cell_loc(results, show.arrows = FALSE)

title: Simulating Spatial Cell-Cell Interactions
text: ext.cif.giv option allows us append custom CIF GIV entries cell gene. can use option simulate spatially variable genes. option function takes kinetic parameter index returns list extra CIF GIV matrices. Using previous layout function, can add extra CIF value based distance origin. Try plotting one spatially variable genes. can see gene expression higher specific spatial region.
code: scmultisim_help("ext.cif.giv") ## ext.cif.giv  (default: NA) ##  Add customized CIF and GIV. The function takes one argument, the kinetic ##   parameter index (1=kon, 2=koff, 3=s). It should return a list of two el ##  ements: the extra CIF matrix (n_extra_cif x n_cells) and the GIV matrix  ##  (n_genes x n_extra_cif). Return NULL for no extra CIF and GIV. ##  should be a function ext_cif <- function(i) {   # We manually set genes 290-300 to be spatially variable   spatial_genes <- 290:300   dist_to_center <- colSums((t(locs) - new_center)^2)   dist_to_center <- dist_to_center / max(dist_to_center)   # 3 is the s parameter   if (i == 3) {     # n_extra_cif x n_cells     ex_cif <- cbind(       # the two CIFs have large values when distance to the center is near 0.5       rnorm(500, 0.5 * dnorm(abs(dist_to_center - 0.5), 0, 0.04), 0.02),       rnorm(500, 0.5 * dnorm(abs(dist_to_center - 0.5), 0, 0.04), 0.02)     )     # n_genes x n_extra_cif     ex_giv <- matrix(0, nrow = 300, ncol = 2)     for (i in spatial_genes) {       # odd genes affected by the first two CIF, even genes affected by the last two CIF       ex_giv[i, ] <- rnorm(2, 1, 0.5)     }     list(ex_cif, ex_giv * 2)   } else {     NULL   } } results <- sim_true_counts(list(   num.cells = 500,   num.genes = 300,   num.cifs = 40,   GRN = NA,   speed.up = T,   cif.sigma = 0.8,   tree = ape::read.tree(text = "(A:1,B:1,C:1,D:1);"),   diff.cif.fraction = 0.8,   ext.cif.giv = ext_cif,   discrete.cif = T,   discrete.pop.size = as.integer(c(120,150,100,130)),   cci = list(     params = lig_params,     max.neighbors = 4,     start.layer = 500,     cell.type.interaction = "random",     layout = layout_fn,     step.size = 1   ) )) ## Experimental speed optimization enabled. ## CCI simulation is enabled. ## Spatial: only the last layer will be simulated. ## Get CIF...Get params...Done ## Simulating...500.. ## Time spent: 0.27 mins plot_cell_loc(results, show.arrows = FALSE,               .cell.pop = log(results$counts[299,] + 1)) + scale_colour_viridis_c()

title: Basic Workflow
text: Call sim_true_counts function simulate true counts. accepts list options input. sim_true_counts important step, able control simulated effects . scMultiSim requires users provide following options: GRN: Gene Regulatory Network. GRN effect unneeded, Provide NA. tree: cell differential tree. cell trajectory unimportant, simply use Phyla1() generate linear tree. scMultiSim provides several example GRN trajectory data: - GRN: GRN_params_100 GRN_params_1139 - Tree: Phyla5(), Phyla3() Phyla1() can visualize data :   Typically, may also want adjust following options control basic cell population: num.cells: Specify number cells. unregulated.gene.ratio num.genes: Control total number genes. discrete.cif: Whether generating discrete continuous cell population. diff.cif.fraction: Control contribution trajectory/cluster specified tree. cif.sigma: Control variation cells along trajectory.
code: data(GRN_params_100)  results <- sim_true_counts(list(   # required options   GRN = GRN_params_100,   tree = Phyla5(),   num.cells = 500,   # optional options   num.cif = 50,   discrete.cif = F,   cif.sigma = 0.1,   do.velocity = T   # ... other options )) #> Time spent: 0.14 mins plot_grn(GRN_params_100) plot_phyla(Phyla5())

text: Simply use add_expr_noise function add technical noise dataset. counts_obs field added results object. function also accepts list options. title: Basic Workflow
text: scMultiSim returns environment following fields: counts: Gene--cell scRNA-seq counts. atac_counts: Region--cell scATAC-seq counts. region_to_gene: Region--gene 0-1 marix indicating corresponding relationship chtomatin regions genes. atacseq_data: “clean” scATAC-seq counts without added intrinsic noise. cell_meta: dataframe containing cell type labels pseudotime information. cif: CIF used simulation. giv: GIV used simulation. kinetic_params: kinetic parameters used simulation. .grn: GRN used simulation. .grn$regulators: list TFs used gene--TF matrices. .grn$geff: Gene--TF matrix representing GRN used simulation. .n: metadata, e.g. .n$cells number cells. .velocity enabled, additional fields: unspliced_counts: Gene--cell unspliced RNA counts. velocity: Gene--cell RNA velocity ground truth. cell_time: pseudotime cell counts generated. dynamic GRN enabled, additional fields: cell_specific_grn: list length n_cells. element gene--TF matrix, indicating cell’s GRN. cell-cell interaction enabled, additional fields: grid: grid object used simulation. grid$get_neighbours(): Get neighbour cells cell . cci_locs: dataframe containing X Y coordinates cell. cci_cell_type_param: dataframe containing CCI network ground truth: ligand-receptor pairs pair cell types. cci_cell_types: continuous cell population, sub-divided cell types along trajectory used simulating CCI. debug session (debug = TRUE), sim field available, environment contains internal states data structures.

text: Table contents Tutorials documentation Installation Shiny App FAQ Contact reference scMultiSim silico simulator generates multi-modality data single-cells, including gene expression, chromatin accessibility, RNA velocity, spatial location cells. takes cell differential tree gene regulatory network (GRN) input, simulates spliced unspliced counts accounting relationships modalities. output single cell gene expression data determined three factors: cell-cell interactions, within-cell GRNs chromatin accessibility. Users can tune effect factor output data set various parameters underlying model. Furthermore, GRN can set time-varying mode network’s structure changes temporally reflect dynamic nature biological networks. also provide options simulate technical variations batch effects. scMultiSim can used benchmark challenging computational tasks single-cell multi-omics data, including inference GRNs, estimation RNA velocity, integration single-cell datasets multiple batches modalities, analysis cell-cell interaction using cell spatial location data. following figure briefly shows results cell differential tree: Connected scATAC-seq scRNA-seq, continuous discrete mode. title: Simulate true scRNA and scATAC counts from the parameters — sim_true_counts
text: scMultiSim returns environment following fields: counts: Gene--cell scRNA-seq counts. atac_counts: Region--cell scATAC-seq counts. region_to_gene: Region--gene 0-1 marix indicating corresponding relationship chtomatin regions genes. atacseq_data: "clean" scATAC-seq counts without added intrinsic noise. cell_meta: dataframe containing cell type labels pseudotime information. cif: CIF used simulation. giv: GIV used simulation. kinetic_params: kinetic parameters used simulation. .grn: GRN used simulation. .grn$regulators: list TFs used gene--TF matrices. .grn$geff: Gene--TF matrix representing GRN used simulation. .n: metadata, e.g. .n$cells number cells. .velocity enabled, additional fields: unspliced_counts: Gene--cell unspliced RNA counts. velocity: Gene--cell RNA velocity ground truth. cell_time: pseudotime cell counts generated. dynamic GRN enabled, additional fields: cell_specific_grn: list length n_cells. element gene--TF matrix, indicating cell's GRN. cell-cell interaction enabled, additional fields: grid: grid object used simulation. grid$get_neighbours(): Get neighbour cells cell . cci_locs: dataframe containing X Y coordinates cell. cci_cell_type_param: dataframe containing CCI network ground truth: ligand-receptor pairs pair cell types. cci_cell_types: continuous cell population, sub-divided cell types along trajectory used simulating CCI. debug session (debug = TRUE), sim field available, environment contains internal states data structures.
